## Summary

Adds a dedicated **speed-optimized routing mode** that scores every provider×model pair in a combo against **TTFT, tokens-per-second, E2E latency, p95 latency, circuit-breaker health, failure rate, and latency stability (std-dev)** — and ranks them so the *fastest reliable* pair wins.

The runtime router (`routerStrategy.ts → LatencyStrategyImpl`) and the new MCP tool (`omniroute_pick_fastest_model`) now share a **single pure scoring core** at `open-sse/services/autoCombo/speedRanking.ts → rankBySpeed()`, so the user-facing preview and the live router pick the same winner.

## What

- **`rankBySpeed(candidates, weights?)`** — pure scoring function. Per-candidate factor breakdown (`ttft/tps/e2e/p95/health/reliability/stability`), weighted composite, OPEN-circuit penalty, deterministic ordering. Tunable weights via `SpeedRankingWeights` (defaults bias toward perceived speed: TTFT 0.30, TPS 0.20, E2E 0.20, p95 0.10, health 0.08, reliability 0.07, stability 0.05).
- **`LatencyStrategyImpl`** refactored to delegate to `rankBySpeed` — the runtime router now benefits from the same rigorous scoring (was previously only `p95LatencyMs` + `errorRate`).
- **New MCP tool `omniroute_pick_fastest_model`** (`schemas/tools.ts` + `tools/advancedTools.ts`) — returns the **full ranked list** with per-factor scores and per-metric breakdown, not just a winner. Optionally applies the result to a target combo by switching its strategy to `auto` + `autoRoutingStrategy: "latency"`. `includeUnhealthy=true` retains OPEN-circuit candidates (default drops them).
- **12 unit tests** in `open-sse/services/autoCombo/__tests__/speedRanking.test.ts` covering: ranking stability, OPEN-circuit drop, weights effect, missing-telemetry neutrality, deterministic tie-breaks, malformed-input rejection, fast-but-flaky vs steady slower, apply-to-combo mutation.

## Why

The current `latency` strategy is naive — it inverts `p95LatencyMs` against the pool max and adds `1 - errorRate`, ignoring **TTFT** (the metric users actually *feel*), **tokens-per-second** (throughput), **E2E latency**, and **latency stability** (a flaky-fast provider can devastate UX). This PR brings the strategy up to par with how users actually think about "fast".

## Test results

- **All 88 related tests pass**: 56 existing `autoCombo.test.ts` + 12 new `speedRanking.test.ts` + 8 existing `routingStrategyTool.test.ts` + 12 un-touched tests in adjacent files.
- 6 pre-existing failures in `open-sse/mcp-server/__tests__/{cacheTools,dbHealthTool,essentialTools,httpAuthContext,toolSearch.catalog,toolSearch.tool}.test.ts` are **unrelated** — caused by missing `safe-regex` dependency on `ccrQuery.ts`, present on upstream `release/v3.8.44` before this PR.
- `tsc --noEmit -p open-sse/tsconfig.json` clean (only pre-existing `baseUrl` TS7 deprecation).
- `eslint` clean on all 6 modified files (only 3 pre-existing `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` warnings in unrelated `memoryTools` registration).

